Here's the registration pattern and the reasoning:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Services
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Holds an `HttpClient` and shared state (cache, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get fresh state — no stale data from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the ViewModel lifetime so each page gets its own ViewModel via constructor injection. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateful services shared app-wide (HTTP clients, caches, settings).
- **Transient** — lightweight, per-use objects (ViewModels, pages).
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET). Avoid unless you create your own scope.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **Transient** or **Scoped** service into a **Singleton** — the shorter-lived service becomes a captive dependency and effectively lives forever.
